[sourcecode language="csharp" highlight="8"]
[Test]
[ExpectedException(
    typeof(ValidationException),
    ExpectedMessage = &quot;Cancelled order cannot be accepted&quot;)]
public void CancelledOrderCannotBeAccepted()
{
    // arrange
    dynamic service = new OrdersService();
    var order = new OrderBuilder().InState(OrderState.Cancelled);
    
    // act
    service.Accept(order);
}
[/sourcecode]

See the <code>dynamic</code> keyword? <code>OrdersService</code> doesn't have <code>Accept</code> method yet but the test compiles and... fails of course. That's good. You can shape your API in tests as you like without even touching implementation (or interfaces). No need for placing <code>NotImplementedException</code> etc. Than you make it gradually work. This trick works especially well with continuous testing tools like <a href="http://www.ncrunch.net/" title="NCrunch">NCrunch</a> or <a href="http://continuoustests.com/" title="Mighty Moose">Mighty Moose</a> which provide almost instant feedback on your test(s).

After making test pass you can change <code>dynamic</code> to <code>var</code> and get static typing (for example allowing automatic renaming with VS refactoring tools).

EDIT 2012/11/10: This idea could be expanded to situations where target type doesn't even exists yet. See i.e.: <a href="https://coderwall.com/p/0uzmdw" target="_blank">https://coderwall.com/p/0uzmdw</a>

In our application we have input data validation implemented in business layer (separate dll). Because we need to report results to user (our UI layer is ASP.NET MVC application) I came up with following interfaces (simplified version):

https://gist.github.com/4079379

It works well until you need to "chain" validators:

[sourcecode language="csharp" highlight="8"]
public bool Validate(IValidationListener listener)
{
    return firstValidator.Validate(listener) &amp;&amp;
        secondValidator.Validate(listener);
}
[/sourcecode]

Validator stops on first error as it should by it doesn't collect all warnings because of "short-circuit" evaluation of "&amp;&amp;". I couldn't use "&amp;" operator because it would change semantics (i.e. evaluate all validators regardless of possible errors). Instead I wanted something like this:

[sourcecode language="csharp" highlight="8"]
public bool Validate(IValidationListener listener)
{
    // stops on error but if there are only warnings reports all of them
    return listener.ListenAll(firstValidator, secondValidator);
}
[/sourcecode]
 
How to do this without changing all implementations of IValidationListener? With extension method and dynamic proxy of course:

https://gist.github.com/4079245

:)

It's time for another adventure with <a href="http://www.castleproject.org/projects/dynamicproxy/">Castle.DynamicProxy</a>. One of the few things I really like in C++ is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resource_Acquisition_Is_Initialization">RAII</a> - for example you can write code like this:

[sourcecode language="cpp"]
class DatabaseContext
{
public:
    virtual ~DatabaseContext()
    {
        CloseConnectionIfOpen();
    }

    void ExecuteNonQuery(string query)
    {
         OpenConnectionIfClosed();
         // and execute query...
    }

    // ...
}

// somewhere else
void DoSomething()
{
    DatabaseContext db;
    db.ExecuteNonQuery(&quot;DELETE * FROM tb_users&quot;);
}
[/sourcecode]

<code>ExecuteNonQuery</code> opens connection to the database and <code>DatabaseContext</code> destructor takes care of closing it regardless if an exception occurred or not. Great! In C# you need more verbose  <code>using/IDisposable</code> or <code>try/finally</code> and... you have a chance to forget about them. 

But Castle.DynamicProxy comes to the rescue:

https://gist.github.com/4109938

Initially this proxy was much simpler but I wanted to support also iterators. Methods returning <code>IEnumerable</code> are tricky. The compiler rewrites them to the state machine i.e. code:

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
IEnumerable&lt;int&gt; GetEnumerable()
{
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++)
        yield return i;
}

List&lt;int&gt; GetList()
{
    var iterator = GetEnumerable(); // for loop not reached yet!
    return iterator.ToList(); // iterator executed
}
[/sourcecode]

Here <code>yield return</code> is only a promise: it will be executed later when the .ToList() is called. As a result proxying those methods is not enough in my situation. What I really need to emulate RAII is to catch the moment after execution of the iterator. But how to do that? Well, the compiler can handle using statements inside iterators:

[sourcecode language="csharp"]
IEnumerable&lt;int&gt; GetEnumerable()
{
    using (... something IDisposable ...)
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++)
            yield return i;
}

List&lt;int&gt; GetList()
{
    var iterator = GetEnumerable();
    return iterator.ToList(); // Dispose() called
}
[/sourcecode]

That's because it returns control to the iterator after leaving foreach loop (ToList method is actually a foreach loop). So the easiest way to do the same is to wrap <code>GetEnumerable</code> with another iterator i.e. effectively proxying resulting iterator object. That's what I did.

Some time ago .... exercise... rereading "Clean Code" by Robert C. Martin.

The problem - stary jak świat - arguments parser:

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
var arg = new Args(&quot;l,p#,d*&quot;, args);
var logging = arg.GetBoolean('l');
var port = arg.GetInt('p');
var directory = arg.GetString('d');
ExecuteApplication(logging, port, directory);
[/sourcecode]

Solution: https://github.com/orient-man/CleanArgs/blob/master/CSharpArgs/Args.cs

As you would expect from Uncle Bob the code is quite good :). It's unit tested, naming is clear, methods are short and you can read it top-down. The main point for refactoring, to ease adding new kinds of arguments, is fulfilled. To add new argument type you need to:
<ul>
	<li>add class new class called marshaller (implementing IArgumentMarshaler)</li>
	<li>if needed add error handling (new ErrorCode + it's string interpretation in ArgsException class)</li>
	<li>connect it in ParseSchemaElement method inside main class (Args)</li>
</ul>
Single Responsibility Principle is taken seriously:
<ul>
	<li> Args: general parsing logic</li>
	<li>Marshsaler classes: handling different kinds of arguments</li>
	<li>ArgsException: error handling + diagnostic information</li>
</ul>
What we could do better? Let's start with Alt-ENTER :)
<h2>Getting more declarative</h2>
This method is ugly and it needs to be updated every time we add new kind of arguments:

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
private void ParseSchemaElement(string element)
{
    var elementId = element[0];
    var elementTail = element.Substring(1);
    ValidateSchemaElementId(elementId);
    if (elementTail.Length == 0)
        marshalers.Add(elementId, new BooleanArgumentMarshaler());
    else if (elementTail == &quot;*&quot;)
        marshalers.Add(elementId, new StringArgumentMarshaler());
    else if (elementTail == &quot;#&quot;)
        marshalers.Add(elementId, new IntegerArgumentMarshaler());
    else if (elementTail == &quot;##&quot;)
        marshalers.Add(elementId, new DoubleArgumentMarshaler());
    else
        throw new ArgsException(
            ErrorCode.InvalidArgumentFormat,
            elementId,
            elementTail);
}
[/sourcecode]

We can extract dictionary declaration and move it to the top:

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
private static readonly IReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, Func&lt;IArgumentMarshaler&gt;&gt;
    Marshalers =
        new Dictionary&lt;string, Func&lt;IArgumentMarshaler&gt;&gt;
        {
            { &quot;&quot;, () =&gt; new BoolArgumentMarshaler() },
            { &quot;*&quot;, () =&gt; new StringArgumentMarshaler() },
            { &quot;#&quot;, () =&gt; new IntArgumentMarshaler() },
            { &quot;##&quot;, () =&gt; new DoubleArgumentMarshaler() }
        };
[/sourcecode]

Now ParseSchemaElement is shorter will stay unchanged for ever:

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
private static IArgumentMarshaler ParseSchemaElement(
    char elementId,
    string elementTail)
{
    ValidateSchemaElementId(elementId);

    Func&lt;IArgumentMarshaler&gt; factory;
    if (!Marshalers.TryGetValue(elementTail, out factory))
        throw new ArgsException(
            ErrorCode.InvalidArgumentFormat,
            elementId,
            elementTail);

    return factory();
}
[/sourcecode]

Notice how we can utilize lamdas and dictionary declaration syntax available in C# but not in Java (at least in 2007).
<h2>SRP to the extreme</h2>
Every marshaler looks similar and has 2 roles:
<ol>
	<li>Parsing: reading enough string args from iterator</li>
	<li>Holding the value and returning it only if caller requests exact type (if not it returns default value)</li>
</ol>

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
public class IntegerArgumentMarshaler : IArgumentMarshaler
{
    private int intValue;

    public void Set(IEnumerator&lt;string&gt; currentArgument)
    {
        if (!currentArgument.MoveNext())
            throw new ArgsException(ErrorCode.MissingInteger);

        try
        {
            intValue = Int32.Parse(currentArgument.Current);
        }
        catch (FormatException)
        {
            throw new ArgsException(ErrorCode.InvalidInteger, currentArgument.Current);
        }
    }

    public static int GetValue(IArgumentMarshaler am)
    {
        var marshaler = am as IntegerArgumentMarshaler;
        return marshaler != null ? marshaler.intValue : 0;
    }
}

public class Args
{
    // ...
    public int GetInt(char arg)
    {
        return IntegerArgumentMarshaler.GetValue(marshalers[arg]);
    }
}
[/sourcecode]

We can improve code above by improving GetValue. Let's move keeping values from marshalers into Args class:

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
public class Args
{
    private readonly IReadOnlyDictionary&lt;char, dynamic&gt; values;
    // ...
}
[/sourcecode]

Now we can use generics and get rid of all variants GetInt/Double/Bool/String etc. but preserve almost the same semantics:

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
public T Get&lt;T&gt;(char arg, T defaultValue = default(T))
{
    dynamic value;
    if (!values.TryGetValue(arg, out value))
        return defaultValue;

    return value is T ? (T)value : defaultValue;
}
[/sourcecode]

Now marshalers only parse arguments and return value immediately:

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
public class IntegerArgumentMarshaler : IArgumentMarshaler
{
    public dynamic Marshal(IEnumerator&lt;string&gt; currentArgument)
    {
        if (!currentArgument.MoveNext())
            throw new ArgsException(ErrorCode.MissingInteger);

        try
        {
            return Int32.Parse(currentArgument.Current);
        }
        catch (FormatException)
        {
            throw new ArgsException(ErrorCode.InvalidInteger, currentArgument.Current);
        }
    }
}
[/sourcecode]

They are actually simple functions disguised into class. They are not "pure" because IEnumerator is changing state but that's ok. We will come back to this later.

<h2>Immutability</h2>

Why we need so many instance variables. Take a look on Args constructor and public API...  

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
private readonly string schema;
private readonly IEnumerable&lt;string&gt; args;
private Dictionary&lt;char, IArgumentMarshaler&gt; marshalers;
private HashSet&lt;char&gt; argsFound;
private IEnumerator&lt;string&gt; currentArgument;

public Args(string schema, IEnumerable&lt;string&gt; args)
{
    this.schema = schema;
    this.args = args;

    Parse();
}
[/sourcecode]

Yep, after parsing none of the variables is modified. ``currentArgument`` is temporary variable, ``marshaler`` and ``argsFound`` used to hold the result but we simplified it already into ``values`` dictionary. Class is basically immutable. We can make it explicit:

[sourcecode language="csharp" light="true"]
private readonly IReadOnlyDictionary&lt;char, dynamic&gt; values;

public Args(string schema, IEnumerable&lt;string&gt; args)
{
    values = ParseArguments(args, ParseSchema(schema));
}
[/sourcecode]

We can pass everything as parameters.

What is the best practice for unit-test names? <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/155436/unit-test-naming-best-practices" target="_blank">CamelCase or underscore or mixed or...?</a>  Good question. But you can side step it somehow. Here is the code I use for transforming unit-test names as displayed in CI server reports e.g. OrdersWithNoProductsShouldFail -&gt; orders with no products should fail:

[sourcecode language="xml"]
&lt;xsl:template name=&quot;SplitCamelCase&quot;&gt;
  &lt;xsl:param name=&quot;text&quot; /&gt;
  &lt;xsl:param name=&quot;digitsMode&quot; select=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;
  &lt;xsl:variable name=&quot;upper&quot;&gt;ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ&lt;/xsl:variable&gt;
  &lt;xsl:variable name=&quot;lower&quot;&gt;abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz&lt;/xsl:variable&gt;
  &lt;xsl:variable name=&quot;digits&quot;&gt;0123456789&lt;/xsl:variable&gt;

  &lt;xsl:if test=&quot;$text != ''&quot;&gt;
    &lt;xsl:variable name=&quot;letter&quot; select=&quot;substring($text, 1, 1)&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;xsl:choose&gt;
      &lt;xsl:when test=&quot;contains($upper, $letter)&quot;&gt;
        &lt;xsl:text&gt; &lt;/xsl:text&gt;
        &lt;xsl:value-of select=&quot;translate($letter, $upper, $lower)&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/xsl:when&gt;
      &lt;xsl:when test=&quot;contains($digits, $letter)&quot;&gt;
        &lt;xsl:choose&gt;
          &lt;xsl:when test=&quot;$digitsMode != 1&quot;&gt;
            &lt;xsl:text&gt; &lt;/xsl:text&gt;
          &lt;/xsl:when&gt;
        &lt;/xsl:choose&gt;
        &lt;xsl:value-of select=&quot;$letter&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/xsl:when&gt;
      &lt;xsl:otherwise&gt;
        &lt;xsl:value-of select=&quot;$letter&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;/xsl:otherwise&gt;
    &lt;/xsl:choose&gt;
    &lt;xsl:call-template name=&quot;SplitCamelCase&quot;&gt;
      &lt;xsl:with-param name=&quot;text&quot; select=&quot;substring-after($text, $letter)&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;xsl:with-param name=&quot;digitsMode&quot; select=&quot;contains($digits, $letter)&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;/xsl:call-template&gt;
  &lt;/xsl:if&gt;
&lt;/xsl:template&gt;
[/sourcecode]

Today I had to optimize a slow running page. We use <a href="http://miniprofiler.com/" title="MiniProfiler">MiniProfiler</a> which makes finding such issues a breeze. But this time it was a little bit more difficult: MiniProfiler showed over 200 hundred SQL queries. How to find the slow ones? Maybe I miss something but it seems there is no built in way to filter MiniProfiler results. I came up with quick jQuery snippet to do just that:

[sourcecode language="javascript"]
// show only slow rows (100ms+)
$('.profiler-info div:last-child')
    .filter(function () {
        // all but having 3+ digit times
        return !$(this).text().match(/^\d{3}.*/);
    })
    .parent()
    .parent()
    .hide()     // tr.profiler-odd
    .next()
    .hide();    // tr.profiler-gap-info
[/sourcecode]

Just run it inside browser's Console window and result should look like this:

<a href="http://orientman.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/filtering-mini-profiler1.gif"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-491" src="http://orientman.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/filtering-mini-profiler1.gif" alt="filtering-mini-profiler" width="529" height="321" /></a>
